012/**
013 * A palette of predefined colors as packed IPT floats, the kind {@link ColorTools} works with.
014 * You can access colors by their constant name, such as {@code OCEAN_BLUE}, by the {@link #NAMED} map using
015 * {@code NAMED.get("Ocean Blue", 0f)}, or by index in the FloatArray called {@link #LIST}. Note that to access a float
016 * color from NAMED, you need to give a default value if the name is not found; {@code 0f} is a good default because it
017 * will not occur in a valid IPT color. You can access the names in a specific order with {@link #NAMES} (which is
018 * alphabetical), {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE} (which is sorted by the hue of the matching color, from red to yellow to blue
019 * (with gray around here) to purple to red again), or {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS} (which is sorted by the intensity of
020 * the matching color, from darkest to lightest). Having a name lets you look up the matching color in {@link #NAMED}.
021 * <br>
022 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 10/13/2020.
023 */
024public class SimplePalette {
025    public static final ObjectFloatMap<String> NAMED = new ObjectFloatMap<String>(50);
026    public static final FloatArray LIST = new FloatArray(50);

648            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
649                final float c1 = NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT), c2 = NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT);
650                final float s1 = ColorTools.saturation(c1), s2 = ColorTools.saturation(c2);
651                if(alphaInt(c1) < 128) return -10000;
652                else if(alphaInt(c2) < 128) return 10000;
653                else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 > 0.05f)
654                    return -1000;
655                else if(s1 > 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)

662            }

674    private static final FloatArray mixing = new FloatArray(4);
675
676    /**
677     * Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed float color.
678     * Color descriptions consist of one or more lower-case words, separated by non-alphabetical characters (typically
679     * spaces and/or hyphens). Any word that is the name of a color in this SimplePalette will be looked up in
680     * {@link #NAMED} and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name words, the colors will be mixed using
681     * {@link FloatColors#mix(float[], int, int)}, or if there is just one color name word, then the corresponding color
682     * will be used. The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the intensity of the described color; likewise,
683     * "rich" and "dull" change the saturation (the difference of the chromatic channels from grayscale). All of these
684     * adjectives can have "-er" or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. Technically,
685     * the chars appended to an adjective don't matter, only their count, so "lightaa" is the same as "lighter" and
686     * "richcat" is the same as "richest". There's an unofficial fourth level as well, used when any 4 characters are
687     * appended to an adjective (as in "darkmost"); it has four times the effect of the original adjective. If a color
688     * name or adjective is invalid, it is considered the same as adding the color {@link #TRANSPARENT}.
689     * <br>
690     * Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve",
691     * and "lightest richer apricot-olive".
692     * @param description a color description, as a lower-case String matching the above format
693     * @return a packed float color as described
694     */
695    public static float parseDescription(final String description) {
696        float intensity = 0f, saturation = 0f;
697        final String[] terms = description.split("[^a-zA-Z]+");
698        mixing.clear();
699        for(String term : terms) {
700            if (term == null || term.isEmpty()) continue;
701            final int len = term.length();
702            switch (term.charAt(0)) {
703                case 'l':
704                    if (len > 2 && term.charAt(2) == 'g') {
705                        switch (len) {
706                            case 9:
707                                intensity += 0.125f;
708                            case 8:
709                                intensity += 0.125f;
710                            case 7:
711                                intensity += 0.125f;
712                            case 5:
713                                intensity += 0.125f;
714                                break;
715                            default:
716                                mixing.add(TRANSPARENT);
717                                break;
718                        }
719                    } else {
720                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
721                    }
722                    break;
723                case 'r':
724                    if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'i') {
725                        switch (len) {
726                            case 8:
727                                saturation += 0.2f;
728                            case 7:
729                                saturation += 0.2f;
730                            case 6:
731                                saturation += 0.2f;
732                            case 4:
733                                saturation += 0.2f;
734                                break;
735                            default:
736                                mixing.add(0f);
737                                break;
738                        }
739                    } else {
740                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, 0f));
741                    }
742                    break;
743                case 'd':
744                    if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'a') {
745                        switch (len) {
746                            case 8:
747                                intensity -= 0.15f;
748                            case 7:
749                                intensity -= 0.15f;
750                            case 6:
751                                intensity -= 0.15f;
752                            case 4:
753                                intensity -= 0.15f;
754                                break;
755                            default:
756                                mixing.add(0f);
757                                break;
758                        }
759                    } else if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'u') {
760                        switch (len) {
761                            case 8:
762                                saturation -= 0.2f;
763                            case 7:
764                                saturation -= 0.2f;
765                            case 6:
766                                saturation -= 0.2f;
767                            case 4:
768                                saturation -= 0.2f;
769                                break;
770                            default:
771                                mixing.add(0f);
772                                break;
773                        }
774                    } else {
775                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, 0f));
776                    }
777                    break;
778                default:
779                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, 0f));
780                    break;
781            }
782        }
783        float result = FloatColors.mix(mixing.items, 0, mixing.size);
784        if(result == 0f) return result;
785
786        if(intensity > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, intensity);
787        else if(intensity < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -intensity);
788
789        if(saturation > 0) result = (ColorTools.enrich(result, saturation));
790        else if(saturation < 0) result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(ColorTools.dullen(result, -saturation));
791        else result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(result);
792
793        return result;
794    }
795    private static final Array<String> namesByHue = new Array<>(NAMES_BY_HUE);
796    private static final FloatArray colorsByHue = new FloatArray(COLORS_BY_HUE);
797    static {
798        int trn = namesByHue.indexOf("transparent", false);
799        namesByHue.removeIndex(trn);
800        colorsByHue.removeIndex(trn);
801    }
802    /**
803     * Given a color as a packed Oklab float, this finds the closest description it can to match the given color while
804     * using at most {@code mixCount} colors to mix in. You should only use small numbers for mixCount, like 1 to 3;
805     * this can take quite a while to run otherwise. This returns a String description that can be passed to
806     * {@link #parseDescription(String)}. It is likely that this will use very contrasting colors if mixCount is 2 or
807     * greater and the color to match is desaturated or brownish.
808     * @param oklab a packed Oklab float color to attempt to match
809     * @param mixCount how many color names this will use in the returned description
810     * @return a description that can be fed to {@link #parseDescription(String)} to get a similar color
811     */
812    public static String bestMatch(final float oklab, int mixCount) {
813        mixCount = Math.max(1, mixCount);
814        float bestDistance = Float.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
815        final int paletteSize = namesByHue.size, colorTries = (int)Math.pow(paletteSize, mixCount), totalTries = colorTries * 81;
816        final float targetL = ColorTools.channelL(oklab), targetA = ColorTools.channelA(oklab), targetB = ColorTools.channelB(oklab);
817        final String[] lightAdjectives = {"darkmost ", "darkest ", "darker ", "dark ", "", "light ", "lighter ", "lightest ", "lightmost "};
818        final String[] satAdjectives = {"dullmost ", "dullest ", "duller ", "dull ", "", "rich ", "richer ", "richest ", "richmost "};
819        mixing.clear();
820        for (int i = 0; i < mixCount; i++) {
821            mixing.add(colorsByHue.get(0));
822        }
823        int bestCode = 0;
824        for (int c = 0; c < totalTries; c++) {
825            for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; i++, e *= paletteSize) {
826                mixing.set(i, colorsByHue.get((c / e) % paletteSize));
827            }
828            int idxI = ((c / colorTries) % 9 - 4), idxS = (c / (colorTries * 9) - 4);
829//            float intensity = idxI * 0.125f, saturation = idxS * 0.2f;
830
831            float result = FloatColors.mix(mixing.items, 0, mixCount);
832            if(idxI > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, 0.125f * idxI);
833            else if(idxI < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -0.15f * idxI);
834
835            if(idxS > 0) result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(ColorTools.enrich(result, 0.2f * idxS));
836            else if(idxS < 0) result = ColorTools.dullen(result, -0.2f * idxS);
837            else result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(result);
838
839            float dL = ColorTools.channelL(result) - targetL, dA = ColorTools.channelA(result) - targetA, dB = ColorTools.channelB(result) - targetB;
840            if(bestDistance > (bestDistance = Math.min(dL * dL + dA * dA + dB * dB, bestDistance)))
841                bestCode = c;
842        }
843
844        StringBuilder description = new StringBuilder(lightAdjectives[(bestCode / colorTries) % 9] + satAdjectives[bestCode / (colorTries * 9)]);
845        for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; e *= paletteSize) {
846            description.append(namesByHue.get((bestCode / e) % paletteSize));
847            if(++i < mixCount)
848                description.append(' ');
849        }
850        return description.toString();
851    }
